             = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = \n| elevation_ft                    = \n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal code of China|Postal code]]\n| postal_code                     = 054000\n| area_code                       = 0319\n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-HE-05]]\n| website                         = {{URL|www.xingtai.gov.cn}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| blank_name                      = [[Vehicle registration plates of China|Licence plate prefixes]]\n| blank_info                      = {{lang|zh-cn|\u5180}}E\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|psp=Hsingtai\n|s=\u90a2\u53f0\n|t=\u90a2\u81fa\n|p=X\u00edngt\u00e1i \n|w=Hsing<sup>2</sup>-tai<sup>2</sup>\n|order=st\n|l=\"temple of Xing\"\n}}\n'''Xingtai''' ({{zh|s={{linktext|\u90a2|\u53f0}} |t=\u90a2\u81fa ''or'' \u90a2\u53f0 |p=X\u00edngt\u00e1i |w=Hsing<sup>2</sup>-tai<sup>2</sup>}}), formerly known as '''[[Xing Prefecture (Hebei)|Xingzhou]]''' and '''Shunde''', is a [[prefecture-level city]] in southern [[Hebei]] province, People's Republic of China. It has a total area of {{convert|12486|km2}} and administers 2 [[district of China|districts]], 2 [[county-level cities]] and 15 [[County (People's Republic of China)|counties]]. At the 2010 census, its population was 7,104,103 inhabitants whom 1,461,809 lived in the built-up (''or metro'') area made of 2 urban districts and Xingtai and Nanhe Counties largely being conurbated now. It borders [[Shijiazhuang]] and [[Hengshui]] in the north, [[Handan]] in the south, and the provinces of [[Shandong]] and [[Shanxi]] in the east and west respectively.\n\n==History==\nXingtai is the oldest city in North China.{{citation needed|date=October 2011}} The history of Xingtai can be traced back 3500 years ago. During the [[Shang Dynasty]], Xingtai functioned as a [[capitals of China|capital city]]. During the [[Zhou Dynasty]], the [[Xing (state)|State of Xing]]{{spaced ndash}}from which the present name derives{{spaced ndash}}was founded in the city. During the [[Warring States period]], the [[state of Zhao]] made Xingtai its provisional capital. The city was known as '''Xindu''' for most of the [[Qin Dynasty]], but after the 207 BC [[Battle of Julu]] (within present-day [[Pingxiang County]], not today's [[Julu County]]), it became known as '''Xiangguo'''. During the [[Sixteen Kingdoms Period]], when the [[Later Zhao]] was founded by [[Shi Le]] of the [[Jie people|Jie]], the capital was again at Xiangguo. During the [[Sui Dynasty|Sui]] and [[Tang Dynasty|Tang dynasties]], the city was known as '''Xingzhou'''.\n\nSui, Tang and [[Song Dynasty|Song]] times saw the zenith of ceramics production in what was the most prolific ceramics center of northern China (rivaling the [[Yue ware]] from the South). The white ware and new technologies developed in the '''Xing Kiln''' mark the transition from proto-porcelain to proper '''[[porcelain]]'''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Song|first1=Xiaoyan|title=The Most Ancient White Porcelain in China|url=http://www.chinatoday.com.cn/ctenglish/2018/cs/201810/t20181011_800143922.html|accessdate=3 March 2020|work=China Today|date=October 11, 2018}}</ref> More than thirty kiln site have been excavated in different subdivisions of today's Xingtai City and a large high-tech museum have been established in Neiqiu County in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Song|first1=Xiaoyan|title=Significant Results from the Excavation of Xing Kiln Site in 2012|url=http://chinesearchaeology.cn/en/News/New_discoveries/2013/1026/43164.html|accessdate=3 March 2020|work=Chinese Archaeology|date=April 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chinese Xingyao Museum|url=http://www.shijiazhuanggd.com/mlxt/yzxt/fjms/jdjs/201902/t20190212_462194.html|accessdate=3 March 2020|work=Shijiazhuang Municipality Official Website}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Xing Kiln Museum / YCA|url=https://www.archdaily.com/917716/xing-kiln-museum-yca|accessdate=3 March 2020|work=ArchDaily|date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Yuan Dynasty]], [[Ming Dynasty|Ming]], and [[Qing Dynasty|Qing dynasties]], Xingtai was called '''Shunteh''' (''Shundefu'') and functioned as a prefecture in China.\n\n==Geography and climate==\nXingtai has a continental, [[monsoon]]-influenced [[semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''BSk''),<ref>Peel, M. C. and Finlayson, B. L. and McMahon, T. A. (2007). [http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2e/Asia_Koppen_Map.png \"Updated world map of the K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification\"]. Hydrol. Earth Syst. Sci. 11: 1633-1644. {{ISSN|1027-5606}}.</ref> characterised by hot, humid summers due to the East Asian monsoon, and generally cold, windy, very dry winters that reflect the influence of the vast Siberian anticyclone. Spring can bear witness to sandstorms blowing in from the Mongolian steppe, accompanied by rapidly warming, but generally dry, conditions. Autumn is similar to spring in temperature and lack of rainfall. The annual rainfall, more than half of which falls in July and August alone, is highly variable and not reliable. In the city itself, this amount has averaged to a meagre {{convert|493|mm|1}} per annum.\n<!--January mean: \u22121.6 \u00b0C, July mean: 27.0 \u00b0C, annual mean: 13.84 \u00b0C-->\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|metric first=y\n|single line=y \n|location = Xingtai (1971\u22122000)\n|Jan high C =  3.9\n|Feb high C =  7.3\n|Mar high C = 13.6\n|Apr high C = 21.9\n|May high C = 27.5\n|Jun high C = 32.1\n|Jul high C = 31.9\n|Aug high C = 30.3\n|Sep high C = 26.9\n|Oct high C = 21.1\n|Nov high C = 12.4\n|Dec high C =  5.9\n|Jan mean C = -1.6\n|Feb mean C =  1.5\n|Mar mean C =  7.9\n|Apr mean C = 15.7\n|May mean C = 21.4\n|Jun mean C = 26.0\n|Jul mean C =  27.0\n|Aug mean C = 25.6\n|Sep mean C = 21.0\n|Oct mean C = 14.7\n|Nov mean C =  6.5\n|Dec mean C =  0.4\n|year mean C = 13.8\n|Jan low C = \u22126.1\n|Feb low C = \u22123.1\n|Mar low C =  2.5\n|Apr low C =